Of course, we often do not need to report the whole output of R-commands, only certain values of the output. For example, below we perform a two-smaple t-test and report only the value of t-statistics and the p-pavue.

mu=0;nu=0.5
x=rnorm(50,mu,1); y=rnorm(50,nu,1) # creating artificial data
ttest=t.test(x,y)

The value of t-statistics in the above evaluation is -0.76 and the p-value is 0.4509.

EXERCISE 2

twoSampleT <- function(mu,nu,m,n,sd,pValue){
  B=1000
  p=numeric(B)
  c = 0
  for (b in 1:B) {
    x=rnorm(m,mu,sd)
    y=rnorm(n,nu,sd)
    p[b]=t.test(x,y,var.equal=TRUE)[[3]]
    if (p[b] < pValue){ c= c+1}
  }
  hist(p,main=c("with",pValue ))
}
twoSampleTNU <- function(mu,nuMin,nuMax,nuStep,m,n,sd,pValue){
  B=1000
  p=numeric(B)
  power = numeric(B)
  for (nu in seq(nuMin,nuMax,by=nuStep)){
    for (b in 1:B) {
      x=rnorm(m,mu,sd)
      y=rnorm(n,nu,sd)
      p[b]=t.test(x,y,var.equal=TRUE)[[3]]
    }
    power[nu]=mean(p<pValue)
  }
  hist(power,main=c("with",pValue ))
}
